4266,IssuesEvent,2016-06-08 05:08:10+00:00,1017451,gorakhargosh/watchdog,5532905,chrisseto,,,opened,Fast moves produces incorrect events,[],[],0,"Note: This is only possible via scripting. I doubt a human could move fast enough to reproduce this problem. Not many people will encounter this problem but I figure there should be some record of it.

This affects Windows and Linux; **not** OSX oddly enough.

Given a directory with a folder called `untitled` and file called `file.txt`.

Running `mv untitled newfolder && mv file.txt newfolder` in bash or the equivalent in windows produces the following events;

```
on_moved(self=<watchdog.tricks.LoggerTrick object at 0x7feb344ac7b8>, event=<DirMovedEvent: src_path='./untitled', dest_path='./newfolder'>)
on_moved(self=<watchdog.tricks.LoggerTrick object at 0x7feb344ac7b8>, event=<FileMovedEvent: src_path='./untitled/file.txt', dest_path='./newfolder/file.txt'>)
on_moved(self=<watchdog.tricks.LoggerTrick object at 0x7feb344ac7b8>, event=<FileMovedEvent: src_path='./file.txt', dest_path='./newfolder/file.txt'>)
```

Notice there is a move event of `untitled/file.txt` -> `newfolder/file.txt` which never happened.

This is due to the [generate_sub_moved_events](https://github.com/gorakhargosh/watchdog/blob/master/src/watchdog/events.py#L576) function listing the folder after the new file has been moved into it. 

Off the top of my head the only way to solve this is doing some introspection before emitting the events which a queue is not quite optimised for. Thoughts?",{},{}
