    users = group.users.all()
    if form.is_valid():
        event = form.save(commit=False)
        if instance is None:
            event.creator = request.user
            event.calendar = calendar
        event.save()
```

In UI, there is a javascript function openDetail in html where I'm displaying the calendar view using the scheduletags month_table as below

``` 
function openDetail(node){
      var eventId = node.getAttribute(""href"").split(""_"")[1];
      var editUrl = ""/events/edit/{{calendar.slug}}/"".concat(eventId);
      var destroyUrl = ""/events/destroy/{{calendar.slug}}/"".concat(eventId);
      var btns = { ""Close"":function(){$(this).dialog(""destroy"");}, ""Edit"":function(){window.location=editUrl;}, ""Destroy"":function(){window.location=destroyUrl;}};
      dia = $(""#edit_dialog"").dialog({'buttons':btns, 'modal':true});
      dia = $($(node).attr(""href"")).dialog({'buttons':btns, 'modal':true, 'title':'Details'});
      dia.dialog('open');
      return false;
    }

//html template code for displaying calendar
{% month_table calendar periods.month ""regular"" %}
```
I have my methods to edit events or destroy events but I want the ability to edit a single occurrence of event rather than complete series of event. I can look to add a new button to openDetail dialog for edit occurrence but what do I pass to it? Is there any input which you can give me to achieve this as it would really help me out. Right now when I create events I don't see any entries in the occurrence tables that I believe will be generated only when it's needed to be persisted.
Looking forward to getting some insights from you on how to achieve this.",{},{}
5589,IssuesEvent,2018-07-05 16:17:09+00:00,3687291,maxcountryman/flask-login,7549938,vishalkuo,,,opened,Remember Me using Alternative Tokens,[],[],0,"<!-- Have a question? Please ask it on https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/flask-login?sort=votes -->
- [x] Ensure you are using the latest PyPI release.
- [x] Read the [CHANGES](https://github.com/maxcountryman/flask-login/blob/master/CHANGES) document thoroughly.
- [x] Provide a clear and simple set of steps to reproduce your issue for others.

I have a use case where my user's `get_id()` uses a `URLSafeTimedSerializer()` with some user properties to generate a session token with an expiry of 60 minutes. If my understanding is correct, the `remember_me` token is a long lived version of the same ID. Unfortunately, this means that when the `remember_me` token is being used to renew a session, it deserializes to a session token that may be expired instead of a user ID. I was wondering if I'm going about things incorrectly or if adding an optional `get_remember_me_id()` to the user class may be helpful.

I'm fairly new to authentication/authorization workflows so if my approach is completely wrong, I'd appreciate pointers on how to fix it.",{},{}
