6708,IssuesEvent,2017-10-30 00:26:41+00:00,34864402,apache/incubator-mxnet,2626883,szha,47359,apache,closed,Cannot resume training while using adam optimizer,[],[],4,"I trained a neural network using adam optimizer. When I tryed to resume training the neural network from checkpoint using mxnet.module.Module.load with load_optimizer_states=True, an error occurred:
```
[15:33:55] E:\mxnet\dmlc-core\include\dmlc/logging.h:300: [15:33:55] e:\mxnet\include\mxnet\./tensor_blob.h:160: Check failed: Device::kDevMask == dev_mask_ TBlob.get: device type do not match specified type
[15:33:56] E:\mxnet\dmlc-core\include\dmlc/logging.h:300: [15:33:56] e:\mxnet\src\engine\./threaded_engine.h:336: [15:33:55] e:\mxnet\include\mxnet\./tensor_blob.h:160: Check failed: Device::kDevMask == dev_mask_ TBlob.get: device type do not match specified type
An fatal error occurred in asynchronous engine operation. If you do not know what caused this error, you can try set environment variable MXNET_ENGINE_TYPE to NaiveEngine and run with debugger (i.e. gdb). This will force all operations to be synchronous and backtrace will give you the series of calls that lead to this error. Remember to set MXNET_ENGINE_TYPE back to empty after debugging.
```

This is because when we load optimizer states, the states of adam optimizer recovered by pickle.loads sit on the device CPU, which is different from the weight of module (commonly sitting on device GPU). Thus when adam_update is called, the error occured.
",{},{}
6712,IssuesEvent,2018-04-11 07:05:26+00:00,34864402,apache/incubator-mxnet,3307514,zhreshold,47359,apache,closed,Use F.reshape_like as F.where condition will cause mismatch gradients,"[{'id': 206159502, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/apache/incubator-mxnet/labels/Bug', 'name': 'Bug', 'color': 'fc2929', 'default': False}, {'id': 273991937, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/apache/incubator-mxnet/labels/C++', 'name': 'C++', 'color': '0052cc', 'default': False}, {'id': 708228884, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/apache/incubator-mxnet/labels/Gluon', 'name': 'Gluon', 'color': 'fbca04', 'default': False}]",[],4,"Note: Providing complete information in the most concise form is the best way to get help. This issue template serves as the checklist for essential information to most of the technical issues.

If the issue is non-technical, feel free to present the information in what you believe is the best form.

## Description
Use F.reshape_like as F.where condition will cause mismatch gradients,

MXNet commit hash:
(Paste the output of `git rev-parse HEAD` here.)
9cf918cbcff32fd2ca4b2d6d53e7f33138d886ee


## Error Message:
```python
mxnet.base.MXNetError: [18:20:44] src/pass/gradient.cc:166: Check failed: (*rit)->inputs.size() == input_grads.size() (2 vs. 3) Gradient function not returning enough gradient
```

## Minimum reproducible example
```
import mxnet as mx
from mxnet import nd
from mxnet import gluon
from mxnet.gluon import nn
from mxnet import autograd


net = nn.HybridSequential()
net.add(nn.Conv2D(3, 3, 1))
net.initialize()

x = nd.ones((1, 3, 64, 64))

class myblock(gluon.Block):
    def __init__(self, **kwargs):
        super(myblock, self).__init__(**kwargs)

    def forward(self, x):
        y = nd.relu(x * 3 + 5)
        z = nd.ones_like(y)
        y = nd.where(z.reshape_like(y) == 1, z, y)  #!!! bug here
        return y

myfunc = myblock()
myloss = gluon.loss.L1Loss()

with autograd.record():
    y = net(x)
    z = myfunc(y)
    loss = myloss(y, z)
    autograd.backward(loss)

print(nd.sum(loss))
```

## What have you tried to solve it?

Use reshape_like itself won't cause problem, only when combining F.where(F.reshape_like(a, b), x, y) will raise error.
",{},{}
