8625,IssuesEvent,2017-08-17 13:41:31+00:00,27086567,scrapinghub/dateparser,2862039,giftig,699596,scrapinghub,opened,Phrasing issues,[],[],0,"I just had a very quick play with this and found some surprising inconsistencies.

```python
In [14]: parse('-30 days at midnight')
Out[14]: datetime.datetime(2017, 7, 18, 14, 39, 14, 370191)

In [15]: parse('-30 days at cucumber')  # To prove it's not simply ignoring midnight entirely

In [16]: parse('-30 days at midnight')
Out[16]: datetime.datetime(2017, 7, 18, 14, 39, 28, 320778)

In [17]: parse('midnight -30 days')
Out[17]: datetime.datetime(2017, 7, 18, 14, 39, 34, 138184)

In [18]: parse('midnight')
Out[18]: datetime.datetime(2017, 8, 17, 0, 0)

In [19]: parse('midnight + 1')
Out[19]: datetime.datetime(2017, 1, 17, 0, 0)

In [20]: parse('midnight + 1 day')
Out[20]: datetime.datetime(2017, 8, 16, 14, 39, 44, 962030)
```

looks like the library needs more work.",{},{}
8632,IssuesEvent,2016-03-03 00:38:06+00:00,27086567,scrapinghub/dateparser,111178,buckket,699596,scrapinghub,opened,UnicodeDecodeError caused by setup.py on Python 3,[],[],0,"When installing `dateparser` on a system which has no or non-utf8 locale variables set (e.g. RTD’s servers), installation fails because you’re making use of the `open()` command in `setup.py` to read things like `README.rst` and `HISTORY.rst`. This happens because Python 3 tries loading those files with the default encoding (which happens to be ASCII), and then fails with an `UnicodeDecodeError`.

You could use `io.open()`, which is available for both Python 2 and 3 and specify the encoding of said files explicitly.

One could argue that this problem is client-sided, but I don’t see any real drawbacks fixing this on your side.

Thanks.",{},{}
8633,IssuesEvent,2016-10-06 08:25:59+00:00,27086567,scrapinghub/dateparser,615559,ishirav,699596,scrapinghub,opened,Richer natural language parsing of times,[],[],0,"It would be nice to be able to parse times that are described in natural language.
For example this works: 
- ""today at noon""
- ""today at 3 pm""

But these don't: 
- ""today at three o'clock"" 
- ""today at three in the afternoon""

Without thinking about it too much, it doesn't seem to be very difficult to add the relevant words as simplifications. What is your position on this?
",{},{}
