8754,IssuesEvent,2016-01-14 17:27:06+00:00,4978045,Parsely/pykafka,723615,emmett9001,779641,Parsely,closed,balanced consumer commits offsets on rebalance,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Parsely/pykafka/labels/backlog', 'name': 'backlog', 'color': '009800'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Parsely/pykafka/labels/question', 'name': 'question', 'color': 'cc317c'}]",[],5,"I don't understand why this is the default behavior even if autocommit mode is not enabled.

It looks like the current library is designed for an at-most-once delivery without actually making the caller in condition to decide it. Probably adding a pre-rebalance callback would be a step forward to this direction.

Also, if I've understood correctly the caller would still be running during the rebalance (I guess the zk callbacks are handled in another thread), this means that it could actually still fetch new messages from the consumer making the at-most-once delivery fail.",{},{}
