8914,IssuesEvent,2016-07-30 06:12:18+00:00,2014929,scikit-image/scikit-image,1189568,rfinck,897180,scikit-image,opened,label2rgb has an undocumented implicit assumption that labels are consecutive non-negative integers,[],[],0,"## Description
An implicit assumption that the labels provided to label2rgb are consecutive non-negative integers can produce unexpected behavior. Two examples below are negative labels resulting in failure to assign background color correctly, and missing labels combined with color cycling.

I can provide a fix unless there is a desire to insist on consecutive non-negative integer labels, in which case this should raise a helpful exception.

## Way to reproduce

```python
labels = np.array([
    [0, 1],
    [2, 0]
])
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 2)
ax[0, 0].imshow(labels)
ax[0, 0].set_title('Nonnegative Labels')
ax[0, 1].imshow(skimage.color.label2rgb(labels, bg_label=0))
ax[0, 1].set_title('RGB with Black Background')
ax[1, 0].imshow(-labels)
ax[1, 0].set_title('Negative Labels')
ax[1, 1].imshow(skimage.color.label2rgb(-labels, bg_label=0))
ax[1, 1].set_title('RGB with Buggy Blue Background')
```
<img width=""522"" alt=""screen shot 2016-07-29 at 10 47 48 pm"" src=""https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1189568/17268399/670f4bea-55de-11e6-8834-c01a5b47338f.png"">

```python
labels = np.array([
    [0, 2],
    [4, 0]
])
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2)
ax[0].imshow(labels)
ax[0].set_title('Grayscale Labels')
ax[1].imshow(skimage.color.label2rgb(labels, colors=[(1, 0, 0), (0, 0, 1)]))
ax[0, 1].set_title('RGB')
```
<img width=""485"" alt=""screen shot 2016-07-29 at 11 08 58 pm"" src=""https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1189568/17268521/5af7a354-55e1-11e6-94c2-39add3706c8a.png"">

scikit-image=0.12.3
Python 2.7.11

",{},{}
8916,IssuesEvent,2016-03-03 16:53:01+00:00,2014929,scikit-image/scikit-image,1950756,jmetz,897180,scikit-image,opened,Remove duplicate mean of template calculation in skimage.feature.match_template,[],[],0,"Reviewing `match_template` I found 

    template_volume = np.prod(template.shape)
    template_ssd = np.sum((template - template.mean()) ** 2)

    if image.ndim == 2:
        xcorr = fftconvolve(image, template[::-1, ::-1],
                            mode=""valid"")[1:-1, 1:-1]
    elif image.ndim == 3:
        xcorr = fftconvolve(image, template[::-1, ::-1, ::-1],
                            mode=""valid"")[1:-1, 1:-1, 1:-1]

    nom = xcorr - image_window_sum * (template.sum() / template_volume)

I.e. `template.mean()` is calculated once, and then further down `template.sum() / template_volume`; presumably we can make this faster using e.g. 

    template_mean = template.mean()

and using that both times it's needed?",{},{}
