10305,IssuesEvent,2016-06-20 21:13:13+00:00,12345160,ansible/tower-cli,1385596,AlanCoding,1507452,ansible,opened,Remove sdict library,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ansible/tower-cli/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ansible/tower-cli/labels/P2', 'name': 'P2', 'color': 'fbca04'}]",[],0,"The requirement `dict.sorted` doesn't have a vendored rpm package associated with it, and it is the only one of our libraries like this. It seems that it's not required for any obvious reason, and we have an ordered dump of YAML in the works right now, which might serve our purposes whenever we need to preserve order.

This issue is to remove the package and work around any problems that come up doing so.",{},{}
10336,IssuesEvent,2017-04-11 12:43:11+00:00,58059785,zalando/expan,1279862,gbordyugov,1564818,zalando,opened,What's the point of *_delta() methods accepting a Result instance?,"[{'id': 370985857, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/zalando/expan/labels/question', 'name': 'question', 'color': 'cc317c', 'default': True}]",[],0,"In the current implementation, all `*_delta()` methods accept a `res` argument, being an instance of the `Result` class. This instance is then updated with the results of the analysis.

On the other hand, other analysis methods, such as `feature_check()`, `sga()`, and `trend()` create a `Result` instance on the fly, populate it with results and return it.

What is the motivation between those two different approaches?",{},{}
