10767,IssuesEvent,2018-02-12 11:32:23+00:00,30509483,clab/dynet,919479,FilippoC,2374376,clab,opened,Sum of an empty vector fails,[],[],0,"Hi,

I do not know if this can be considered as a bug, but the sum of an empty vector results in a runtime error:
```
dytest was compiled with optimization - stepping may behave oddly; variables may not be available.
Process 2070 stopped
* thread #1, queue = 'com.apple.main-thread', stop reason = EXC_BAD_ACCESS (code=1, address=0x0)
    frame #0: 0x00000001000018f4 dytest`dynet::Expression dynet::detail::f<dynet::Sum, std::__1::vector<dynet::Expression, std::__1::allocator<dynet::Expression> > >(xs=size=1) at expr.h:111 [opt]
   108  namespace detail {
   109  template <typename F, typename T>
   110  Expression f(const T& xs) {
-> 111    ComputationGraph *pg = xs.begin()->pg;
   112    std::vector<VariableIndex> xis(xs.size());
   113    int i = 0;
   114    for (auto xi = xs.begin(); xi != xs.end(); ++xi) xis[i++] = xi->i;
Target 0: (dytest) stopped.
```

Here is the code:
```
  1 #include <vector>
  2
  3 #include ""dynet/dynet.h""
  4 #include ""dynet/expr.h""
  5
  6 int main(int argc, char* argv[])
  7 {
  8     dynet::initialize(argc, argv);
  9     dynet::ComputationGraph cg;
 10
 11     std::vector<dynet::Expression> v;
 12
 13     auto e = dynet::input(cg, 4);
 14     //v.push_back(e);
 15
 16     dynet::sum(v);
 17 }
```

This may happens when working with structured losses (e.g. hinge loss). It is convenient to have a function which adds to a vector each wrongly predicted parts and then returns the sum of them.
A workaround is to write down something like `return v.size() > 0 ? dynet::sum(v) : dynet::input(cg, 0)`.",{},{}
10775,IssuesEvent,2017-10-19 17:47:24+00:00,30509483,clab/dynet,5766101,huzecong,2374376,clab,opened,Exceptions not thrown when multiplying scalar values of different batch sizes,[],[],0,"Consider the following example:

```python
import dynet as dy

x = dy.inputTensor([1, 2, 3], batched=True)
print(x.dim())  # ((1,), 3)

y = dy.inputTensor([1, 2], batched=True)
print(y.dim())  # ((1,), 2)

z = x * y  # should throw an exception
print(z.dim())  # the resulting expression had a batch size of 3
```

On the other hand, `x + y` or `dy.cmult(x, y)` does throw an exception, which is the expected behavior.  As far as I have tested, this bug only happens for scalar expressions.",{},{}
10778,IssuesEvent,2017-02-09 21:03:40+00:00,30509483,clab/dynet,398875,neubig,2374376,clab,closed,CMake requires the full Eigen path in some environments,"[{'id': 439661280, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/clab/dynet/labels/minor%20bug', 'name': 'minor bug', 'color': 'f9d0c4', 'default': False}]",[],2,"In some environments, the [installations script](http://dynet.readthedocs.io/en/latest/python.html) fails. CMake seems to require the full path for Eigen, and not the relative one. I couldn't figure out why it happens in some environments and not others. Maybe worth adding a note. ",{},{}
