11096,IssuesEvent,2017-06-15 20:45:06+00:00,16316451,GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python,247555,tswast,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,opened,BigQuery: Add QueryResults.reload() function which calls getQueryResults,"[{'id': 82126549, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python/labels/api:%20bigquery', 'name': 'api: bigquery', 'color': 'c0c0c0', 'default': False}]",[],0,"https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/docs/reference/rest/v2/jobs/getQueryResults

One of the things I learned when talking to the BigQuery API folks is that the recommended way to run a query is to create a query job and then call `getQueryResults()` until the `jobComplete` property is `true`.

The reason for this is that a call to get the job resource will return immediately, whereas `getQueryResults` will return after a timeout or the query is complete, whichever comes first. With `getQueryResults` users get their data faster.

This means the code for waiting for a query job to complete would change from

    while True:
       query_ job.reload()
        if query_job.state == 'DONE':
            return
        time.sleep(1)

to something like

    query_results = query_job.results()
    while not query_results.complete:
        query_results.reload()
        # No need for sleep, since reload should wait for timeout",{},{}
11108,IssuesEvent,2018-05-23 21:14:28+00:00,16316451,GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python,250995,theacodes,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,closed,PubSub: Batching / Duplicates issue when consuming messages sequentially.,"[{'id': 139685153, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python/labels/api:%20pubsub', 'name': 'api: pubsub', 'color': 'f8f8f8', 'default': False}, {'id': 544604243, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python/labels/priority:%20p2', 'name': 'priority: p2', 'color': 'fef2c0', 'default': False}, {'id': 77438580, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python/labels/type:%20bug', 'name': 'type: bug', 'color': 'd93f0b', 'default': False}]",[],6,"## Env Info 
python 3.5.3
google-cloud-pubsub==0.32.0
macOS 10.13.3

## Problem
I’m currently dealing with a weird issue on PubSub. In the video in the link there are two subscribers that process messages from the same subscription sequentially with thread.Lock and flow_control = 1. The ack deadline of the topic is 10s. 

With a publisher I first send 300 messages (just the number i) to the topic in one batch. The subscribers print the message.

As you can see in the beginning only one of the subscribers starts to receive messages. After some number of messages the second one kicks in (it seems to be number of messages not time - I tried it with adding a sleep in processing the messages). But both subscribers are processing the same messages.

After I clear the buffer I sent the same number of messages again with a batch_size of only 20. Then the two subscribers act as expected. They start at the same time and don’t process duplicate messages.

I assume the problem has to do with how the python consumers pull and caches messages. 

Here's the video:
https://www.useloom.com/share/0b1299d4961b46cd83efc3c13f2a414a

And code to reproduce the issue:
[batching_issue_publisher_and_subscriber.zip](https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python/files/1775064/batching_issue_publisher_and_subscriber.zip)



",{},{}
