12853,IssuesEvent,2016-03-01 15:55:48+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1672353,wulmer,6392739,conda,opened,Regression of issue 896,[],[],0,"Hi,

since commit bc9241606ef324f1b926f077fe3940d020d3f013 there is a regression on the previous issue https://github.com/conda/conda/issues/896 where running conda takes endlessly on Windows when Anaconda is installed in a directory not writable by the normal user.

Can anyone explain why the original fix 495ea74fd95bd57a591d907a64c771260a1bdcb7 was reverted a year later in bc9241606ef324f1b926f077fe3940d020d3f013 ?

This makes Anaconda totally unusable in a Windows installation *For all users*.

Wolfgang",{},{}
12855,IssuesEvent,2017-01-31 08:55:21+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,17023133,RedDevil91,6392739,conda,opened,CondaHTTPError - Proxy authentication needed    ,[],[],0,"Hi

I have upgraded miniconda version from 4.0.5 to 4.2.12 and now I have an issue with proxy authentication. If we (at work) want to install packages with conda then I get the following error:

```
Fetching package metadata ...

CondaHTTPError: HTTP None None
for url <None>

An HTTP error occurred when trying to retrieve this URL.
ConnectionError(MaxRetryError(""HTTPSConnectionPool(host='repo.continuum.io', port=443): Max retries exceeded with url: /pkgs/free/win-64/repodata.json.bz2 (Caused by ProxyError('Cannot connect to proxy.', error('Tunnel connection failed: 407 authenticationrequired',)))"",),)
```

In the .condarc file the proxy address and port number is properly set without username:password. So currently my .condarc look like the following:

```
proxy_servers:

      http: http://address:port

      https: https://address:port

```



The username and the password is missing because we are using the conda from work and the IT doesn't allow to store the password and username in a file without encryption.

Is this because the newer version of conda doesn't support the proxy settings authentication from command line? Because the old version asked for username and password if conda couldn't find them in the .condarc file.

Thanks",{},{}
12858,IssuesEvent,2016-06-13 06:22:34+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,2233820,lch14forever,6392739,conda,opened,Conda deactivate does not execute deactivate.d/env_vars.sh,[],[],0,"I found the function of setting environmental variable within a conda env useful, but it did not seem to do the correct thing when the environment was deactivated.

I have created the following two scripts:
* anaconda/envs/nanopore/etc/conda/activate.d/env_vars.sh
~~~~
#!/bin/sh
export OLD_PATH=$PATH
export PATH=/etc/alternatives/java_sdk_1.8.0/bin:$PATH
export JAVA_HOME=/etc/alternatives/java_sdk_1.8.0/
~~~~
* anaconda/envs/nanopore/etc/conda/deactivate.d/env_vars.sh
~~~~
#!/bin/sh
export PATH=$OLD_PATH
unset JAVA_HOME
echo ""done"" 1>&2
~~~~

When the environment was activated, the environmental variables were set correctly. However, the script that unset the variables did not seem to be sourced (No print out of the message ""done"" at all).

~~~~
14:19:45|lich@n066|conda$ source deactivate
discarding /mnt/software/unstowable/anaconda/envs/nanopore/bin from PATH
~~~~",{},{}
