13531,IssuesEvent,2018-08-12 08:07:03+00:00,13258039,aio-libs/aiohttp,356399,asvetlov,7049303,aio-libs,closed,DeprecationWarning: Inheritance class Session from ClientSession is discouraged,"[{'id': 58986079, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw1ODk4NjA3OQ==', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/aio-libs/aiohttp/labels/question', 'name': 'question', 'color': 'cc317c', 'default': True}]",[],1,"Hey, not really a bug or an issue but I like inheriting from the ClientSession object when creating an API wrapper that has custom logic for requests (such as hashing of payloads) and custom headers etc.

Just wondering why this seems to be depreciated and if there's an alternative.",{},{}
13536,IssuesEvent,2017-06-27 16:59:26+00:00,13258039,aio-libs/aiohttp,2501327,litwisha,7049303,aio-libs,opened,_CoroGuard cannot be awaited,[],[],0,"## Long story short

<!-- 
1) [_CoroGuard.](https://github.com/aio-libs/aiohttp/blob/master/aiohttp/helpers.py#L65) class has no implementation for `__await__` method, only `__iter__`. 
That's why`_CoroGuard` instance cannot be `awaited`, just `yielded from`.
`ClientSession.close` method returns `_CoroGuard` instance, and if it's not awaited, it raises `DeprecationWarning`
2) According to warning [message](https://github.com/aio-libs/aiohttp/blob/master/aiohttp/client.py#L538), I can assume that `ClientSession.close` method is not supposed to be awaited. 
Thus, `_CoroGuard` should check that it was not awaited(remove `not` from `if not self._awaited` in `__del__` method, **BUT** `_CoroGuard` is supposed to check that coroutine actually was awaited(conflict). 
Currently, `_CoroGuard` is used only for `ClientSession.close`.
-->

## Expected behaviour

<!-- `_CoroGuard` can be awaited -->

## Actual behaviour

<!-- `_CoroGuard` cannot be awaited -->

## Steps to reproduce

<!-- 
```
#!/usr/bin/env python
import aiohttp
import asyncio


async def coro_function(loop):
    session = aiohttp.ClientSession(loop=loop)
    await session.close()


if __name__ == '__main__':
    loop = asyncio.get_event_loop()
    try:
        loop.run_until_complete(coro_function(loop))
    finally:
        loop.close()

```

 -->

## Your environment

<!--
OS X 10.12.3
python 3.6.0
aiohttp==2.2.0
 -->
