13710,IssuesEvent,2016-11-10 16:42:09+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,9889312,BoPeng,7388996,jupyter,opened,Can the look of jupyter notebook be customized in any way according to kernel status?,[],[],0,"I have developed a [Script of Scripts](https://github.com/BoPeng/SOS) kernel that allows switching between different kernels using magics such as `%use R`, and `%with R`. It is working reasonably well but there is a small problem with the current implementation, namely there is no hint that which kernel is currently active. Is it possible to, for example, change the background of notebook according to current kernel? 

In addition, it would be useful if I can mark each cell with the kernel used so that I can get a notebook with cells in different colors. For example

```
[white SoS cell]
    import pandas as pd
    data = pd.read_excel('data.xls')
[purple R cell]
    %with R -i data -o m
    m <- apply(data, 1, median)
[white SoS cell]
    print(m)
```

I have a feeling that this could be done in javascript, but I currently have no idea how the browser (javascript) interacts with the kernel. Any suggestion or code example would be greatly appreciated.",{},{}
13749,IssuesEvent,2016-02-25 15:12:40+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,3856586,Phyks,7388996,jupyter,opened,Untrusted notebook user experience,[],[],0,"Hi,

I got some issues with `%matplotlib notebook` which was discarding my figures when reloading the notebook, and replacing them with `<IPython.core.display.Javascript object>`. I could not figure out why, and I discovered it was due to the fact that my notebook was not trusted.

Maybe it could be a good idea to add a big warning bar on top of the notebook if running in untrusted mode, stating something like ""this notebook runs in untrusted mode, some features will be disabled."", and it could improve user experience a lot.

Thanks",{},{}
