14125,IssuesEvent,2017-10-21 12:25:25+00:00,98336690,deepmind/pysc2,195271,Inoryy,8596759,deepmind,opened,Redirecting stderr of SC2 process,[],[],0,"Currently there's no way to redirect SC2 proc stderr output (i.e. `Game has started.` messages) except for doing it globally, which is quite annoying if you're running multiple SC2 env instances.

The way it should be done from within Python is by allowing `stderr=...` parameter in the `subprocess.Popen` call during [StarcraftProcess::_launch call](https://github.com/deepmind/pysc2/blob/master/pysc2/lib/sc_process.py#L132). One way to set is could be a global flag since project relies on `gflags` already.",{},{}
14184,IssuesEvent,2017-02-19 13:09:49+00:00,39858489,juju-solutions/charms.reactive,1492981,galgalesh,8684561,juju-solutions,opened,Layered interface layers,"[{'id': 525334251, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/juju-solutions/charms.reactive/labels/Epic', 'name': 'Epic', 'color': '3E4B9E', 'default': False}]",[],0,"We need a way to share code between interface layers.

# `rest-api` extends `http`

Consider a database WololoDB® with an HTTP REST API. The charm for WololoDB should implement the generic `http` interface to connect to reverseproxies, loadbalancers, https endpoints etc. The charm should also implement a specific `wololodb` interface for clients who want to talk to the database. So we have two interface layers:

- `http` sends the hostname and the port and tells Juju that it can connect to other charms implementing the `http` interface.
- `wololodb` sends the hostname and port and tells Juju that it can connect to other charms implementing the `wololodb` interface.

Although both interfaces are identical, they need to be separate so that Juju knows that a `wololodb` client can only connect to a WololoDB server, not all HTTP servers.

This maps very cleanly to layers, the `wololodb` interface uses the `http` interface as base interface layer.

Whatever we come up with for reactive 2.0 should enable this kind of layered approach to interfaces.

# Totally epic

Juju should understand the API inheritance. The HAProxy charm is a great use-case for this. The `reverseproxy` relationship has two ""modes"", the default mode compatible with the normal `http` interface, and an advanced mode where more info is shared over the relationship.

This would result in two interfaces

 - `http`
 - `reverseproxy` which `includes: ['http']`

When an operator connects a charm to haproxy, Juju knows that the `reverseproxy` relationship is preferred over the `http` relationship if both charms implement that interface.",{},{}
