16204,IssuesEvent,2018-08-29 15:33:17+00:00,43091756,hackingmaterials/matminer,14810408,albalu,14116185,hackingmaterials,closed,MultipleFeaturizer with mixed dtypes,[],[],4,"When output data is mixture of numbers and str (pandas object) MultipleFeaturizer converts all of them to object which is pretty bad. For example, the following test under ""test_composition.py"" would fail.

```
def test_multifeat_dtypes(self):
    featzers = [
        Stoichiometry(),
        AtomicOrbitals()
    ]
    multifeat = MultipleFeaturizer(featzers)
    df = multifeat.featurize_dataframe(self.df, col_id='composition')
    self.assertEqual(set(df.dtypes.astype(str)), {'float64', 'int64', 'object'})
```

if I override get_dataframe inside MultipleFeaturizer, the problem is fixed (also the progress bars work for each featurizer as opposed to only for MultipleFeaturizer). However, it seems like it fails some caching tests. @WardLT , this seems to be related to your code? Unfortunately, at the moment, I don't have a solution to both these issues:

```
def featurize_dataframe(self, df, col_id, **kwargs):
    multiindex = kwargs.get(""multiindex"", False)
    for i, featzer in enumerate(self.featurizers):
        if i>0 and multiindex:
            col_id = ('Input Data', col_id)
            multiindex = False
        df = featzer.featurize_dataframe(df, col_id, **kwargs)
    return df
```",{},{}
16212,IssuesEvent,2016-07-15 20:13:50+00:00,42082724,MycroftAI/adapt,17013620,ethanaward,14171097,MycroftAI,opened,Issues with previously registered vocab terms and regex,[],[],0,"@HeinzSchmidt was talking earlier about having troubles with properly triggering his shopping skill, so I started testing it. He registered regex that looks like `(?P<ShopVerb>.*) (?P<ShopItem>.*) to (?P<ShopLocation>.*)`, and was trying to use it to match to `add onions to my shopping list`, with add as the `ShopVerb`, onions as the `ShopItem`, and my shopping list as the `ShopLocation`. However, he was getting back `my shopping` as the location rather than `my shopping list`. According to [an online regex tester](https://regex101.com/r/pA8xU3/5), this is incorrect. 

I did some testing, and found out that the problem persists with other syntax - `add onions to my shopping mouse`, for example, returns `my shopping` as the location, chopping off `mouse` at the end. Other similar words such as `terminal` were also getting cut off, and I realized that mouse and keyboard were registered as vocab by the desktop launcher skill. When I added desktop launcher to the blacklisted skills, the problem with those two words stopped. I did a quick check, and `list` has been registered as vocab to scheduled skills. I added those to the blacklist, and I started getting `my shopping list` back again.

This means that there is some issue with Adapt parsing regex when there is another vocab term in the expression. From my testing, it also seems to be localized to be only at the end of sentences, although that may not be true.
",{},{}
