16521,IssuesEvent,2016-11-08 16:30:07+00:00,40249032,cfn-sphere/cfn-sphere,3943275,marco-hoyer,15830872,cfn-sphere,opened,Unintended updates caused by config-git-repository tag,"[{'id': 244487867, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/cfn-sphere/cfn-sphere/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929', 'default': True}]",[],0,"With version 0.1.34 cfn-sphere automatically adds a config-git-repository tag with the repo url as value if the stack configuration resides within a git repository. This stack level tag gets propagated to the stacks resources depending on the resource type. In bad cases, the tag is automatically added to an RDS parameter group. This causes a database downtime which should not happen at all. 

This might be acceptable but possible inconsistencies are much worse. When the git project containing the stack configuration was checked out with https, the repository url is something like https://host/space/repo.git but when checked out with ssh it might be user@host:space/repo.git. This causes the config-git-repository tag value to differ depending on the environment on which the update is made.",{},{}
16568,IssuesEvent,2016-09-15 08:04:29+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,22167799,rlubos,16142269,openthread,opened,Router ID 62 treated as incorrect Router ID,[],[],0,"Hi,
I've looked through the OpenThread code, and I've noticed that in OpenThread (mostly in mle_router.cpp, the value kMaxRouterId (62) is treated as incorrect Router ID, while according to the specification this value is still a valid Router ID. I'm affraid that this might generate problems with interoperability with other stacks.",{},{}
16589,IssuesEvent,2016-07-24 18:53:13+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,106395,mszczodrak,16142269,openthread,opened,strnlen missing in older gcc versions,[],[],0,"In spinel.c we are using strnlen. This function is not defined in arm-none-eabi-gcc-4.8.3, which is still a common version.

Perhaps we can avoid using this function, or add a local version when it's missing, or we can add configure check AC_FUNC_STRNLEN to catch that situation early.

Some background reading about the problem: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/30203551/undefined-reference-to-strnlen-despite-string-h-include ",{},{}
