16878,IssuesEvent,2018-01-30 15:52:34+00:00,3277149,pyFFTW/pyFFTW,6528957,grlee77,16965121,pyFFTW,closed,Function empty_aligned fails on certain dtypes...,"[{'id': 318772912, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pyFFTW/pyFFTW/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'e11d21', 'default': True}]",[],22,"When building the FFT, the function `builders._utils._Xfftn` is eventually called. This calls `builders._utils._compute_array_shapes` to determine the appropriate `input_shape` and `output_shape` and then eventually `pyfftw.empty_aligned(output_shape, output_dtype)`. We were getting the following exception when building FFTs on very large `complex64` arrays:

```
ValueError: negative dimensions are not allowed
```

This was eventually traced to the `builders._compute_array_shapes` call which produced a tuple of `int32` dimensions for the respective shape tuples. I assume they were `int32` as a consequence of working on `complex64` arrays. In any event, the negative dimensions were probably due to integer wrapping for numbers greater than the capacity of `int32`. See the following instructive example, which was carried out using the pre-built `pyFFTW-0.10.1-cp34-none-win_amd64.whl`::

```
>>> dtype = np.dtype(np.complex64)
>>> shape = (np.int32(2**14), np.int32(2**14))
>>> pyfftw.empty_aligned(shape, dtype)

ValueError: negative dimensions are not allowed
```

And a little bit of tweaking...

```
>>> shape = (np.int32(2**14 - 1), np.int32(2**14))
>>> pyfftw.empty_aligned(shape, dtype)
array([[ 0.+0.j,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j, ...,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j],
       [ 0.+0.j,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j, ...,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j],
       [ 0.+0.j,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j, ...,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j],
       ..., 
       [ 0.+0.j,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j, ...,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j],
       [ 0.+0.j,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j, ...,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j],
       [ 0.+0.j,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j, ...,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j,  0.+0.j]], dtype=complex64)
```

In order to perform the required FFTs, I changed `builders._compute_array_shapes` so that it **always** casts the shape to a tuple of Python `int`s rather than something based on the provided `dtype`. For us anyway, there does not seem to be a good reason for the shape tuple to be anything other than high capacity integers... the memory footprint is obviously dominated by the `dtype` of the actual array rather than that of its metadata.

I just wanted to bring this to your attention... I didn't know if this was expected behavior or not. In any event, we did have to make a hack in your package, which we always try to avoid! :)
",{},{}
