18125,IssuesEvent,2018-08-17 02:46:36+00:00,35531022,opendatacube/datacube-core,1428024,Kirill888,26125288,opendatacube,opened,Propose to add new field to eo metadata,"[{'id': 919049783, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw5MTkwNDk3ODM=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/opendatacube/datacube-core/labels/discussion', 'name': 'discussion', 'color': '5d19a0', 'default': False}, {'id': 210910444, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwyMTA5MTA0NDQ=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/opendatacube/datacube-core/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}, {'id': 848431225, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw4NDg0MzEyMjU=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/opendatacube/datacube-core/labels/querying/searching', 'name': 'querying/searching', 'color': 'c4d0fc', 'default': False}]",[],0,"Many (most?) data sources have  some structure to the way they capture data. Typically there is some sort of spatial partitioning, there is a finite set of regions and they get observed with some regularity. A footprint of any dataset is not completely arbitrary or unique. There often exists a ""native"" spatial binning, several datasets, captured at different times but covering the same ""region"" might not have exactly the same footprint, but they will have a ""significant"" overlap, and are likely to share the same projection.  

In case of Landsat that region is a ""scene path,row"", in case of ingested products on NCI it's Albers tile, for Sentinel it's MGRS code.

I think it is worthwhile to keep that ""native spatial grouping"" information, and I think it's generic enough to justify adding it to the default metadata type `eo`.

Possible names:

- `region_code`  
- `regioncode` (like postcode)
- `region_id`
- `spatial_group_id`

We won't promise much: 

- Uniquely identifies some spatial region
- Datasets with the same `region_code` cover roughly the same area
- There is a finite set of spatial regions (much less than number of datasets in the collection)
- No interpretation of `region_code`, no spatial info of any kind, just an opaque label
- No spatial ""ordering""

This would allow grouping of datasets based on ""collection specific"" spatial relations, this could be useful for certain types of processing.",{},{}
18129,IssuesEvent,2017-09-13 00:26:45+00:00,35531022,opendatacube/datacube-core,8537264,uchchwhash,26125288,opendatacube,closed,Index should not support serialization,[],[],2,"As the `_db` attribute of a `datacube.index._api.Index` object refers to a `PostgresDb` connection, it should not support serialization.

### Expected behaviour
The following code should raise a `TypeError`:

```python
import pickle
from datacube import Datacube

dc = Datacube(app='issue285')
pickle.dumps(dc.index)
```

### Actual behaviour
Trying to serialize a `PostgresDb` object only issues a warning:
`Serializing PostgresDb engine postgresql://ia1511@130.56.244.105:6432/datacube`

### Steps to reproduce the behaviour
The interaction of this issue with logging may lead to unexpected behavior. In the current `develop` branch, the above code raises an exception:
```
TypeError                                 Traceback (most recent call last)
/g/data1/u46/users/ia1511/Work/code/issue285/test-simple.py in <module>()
      3 
      4 dc = Datacube(app='issue285')
----> 5 pickle.dumps(dc.index)

TypeError: can't pickle _thread.RLock objects
```
when run in `ipython`, but not when run by the `python` interpreter.

When logging is turned on:
```python
from logging import getLogger, StreamHandler
import pickle
from datacube import Datacube

logger = getLogger(__name__)
logger.addHandler(StreamHandler())

dc = Datacube(app='issue285')
pickle.dumps(dc.index)
```
both interpreters throw the `TypeError`. Note that, in principle, the issue is not just that `RLock` objects cannot be serialized, but that currently `Index` objects can.

### Environment information

* Which ``datacube --version`` are you using?
  - stable: `Open Data Cube core, version 1.5.2`
  - develop: `Open Data Cube core, version 1.5.1+150.g71175f1.dirty`


* What datacube deployment/enviornment are you running against?
`agdc-py3-prod/1.5.2`
",{},{}
18139,IssuesEvent,2018-04-13 01:59:05+00:00,79083614,python-trio/trio,609896,njsmith,26335827,python-trio,opened,serve_listeners resource exhaustion handling is probably broken on Windows,[],[],0,"Looking at https://github.com/twisted/twisted/pull/996/ led me to investigate more the difference between `EMFILE` and `WSAEMFILE`... the latter is the special ""winsockets"" version of `EMFILE`, and apparently they are actually different:

```
In [2]: errno.EMFILE
Out[2]: 24

In [3]: errno.WSAEMFILE
Out[3]: 10024
```

And right now `serve_listeners` has special handling for `EMFILE`, but not `WSAEMFILE`... so it's probably broken.

We should:

* Add the WSA variants to the list of errnos here: https://github.com/python-trio/trio/blob/7b7b7d1431644233a2c06928802be6cdca2e35c6/trio/_highlevel_serve_listeners.py#L11-L16
* Double-check if we need to modify the list in `SocketListener`: https://github.com/python-trio/trio/blob/7b7b7d1431644233a2c06928802be6cdca2e35c6/trio/_highlevel_socket.py#L291-L311
* Modify our EMFILE test so that it actually provokes a real EMFILE, instead of a fake one like we do now: https://github.com/python-trio/trio/blob/7b7b7d1431644233a2c06928802be6cdca2e35c6/trio/tests/test_highlevel_serve_listeners.py#L102-L105",{},{}
18148,IssuesEvent,2018-03-22 08:34:42+00:00,79083614,python-trio/trio,609896,njsmith,26335827,python-trio,opened,Should we have a way to block open_tcp_stream from connecting to certain hosts?,"[{'id': 523592585, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/python-trio/trio/labels/design%20discussion', 'name': 'design discussion', 'color': '0052cc', 'default': False}, {'id': 523593177, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/python-trio/trio/labels/polish', 'name': 'polish', 'color': 'f9d0c4', 'default': False}]",[],0,"I was reading https://www.blackhat.com/docs/us-17/thursday/us-17-Tsai-A-New-Era-Of-SSRF-Exploiting-URL-Parser-In-Trending-Programming-Languages.pdf , and there are a few examples that follow this pattern:

* you have some program running behind your firewall (e.g., the code running Github, or Wordpress)
* it wants to make an outgoing HTTP request, but the destination URL is at least somewhat under the control of an untrusted user (e.g., Github webhooks)
* you want to make sure that user doesn't direct the request at some sensitive behind-the-firewall service and pwn you
* so you have some check, like you blacklist any URL that says `localhost` in it
* but doing this correctly is extremely tricky, so everyone screws it up, and they get pwned.

The only correct place to do this check is after you've done the final conversion to a (normalized) IP address, and even there it has subtleties (e.g. `sock.connect(0.0.0.0, port)` seems to connect to localhost for me, and ipv4-mapped addresses are a thing that someone could potentially put in an AAAA record if they wanted to be perverse). If you're using `open_tcp_stream` – and we'd hope that HTTP clients on top of trio will use `open_tcp_stream`! – then that means that the checking has to happen inside `open_tcp_stream`.

One option would be to provide a `blacklist_targets=...` argument, that gives a list of `ipaddress.IPv{4,6}Network` objects, and for each resolved address checks if they fall into any of the given networks, and raises an error if so. The `ipaddress` module also provides mechanisms to check if an address is private, reserved, loopback, etc., which might be useful here.

Or I guess we could be even more minimal, and let the user pass in a `validate_target=...` function, that gets called on all the targets, and can raise an error or return `False` or whatever to indicate a bad target.

We should check with urllib3/requests maintainers whether this is something they would actually use.",{},{}
