18478,IssuesEvent,2018-08-13 02:38:08+00:00,123377553,MetPX/sarracenia,394117,petersilva,36943571,MetPX,opened,sr_subscribe gives bogus SSL failure message...,[],[],0,"it seems harmless, but on startup, sr_subscribe, when consuming the first message, and one is connecting to an SSL broker, will print:

```
Exception ignored in: <bound method _AbstractTransport.__del__ of <amqplib.client_0_8.transport.SSLTransport object at 0x7fca748f42e8>>
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""/usr/lib/python3/dist-packages/amqplib/client_0_8/transport.py"", line 97, in __del__
    self.close()
  File ""/usr/lib/python3/dist-packages/amqplib/client_0_8/transport.py"", line 139, in close
    self.sock.shutdown(socket.SHUT_RDWR)
  File ""/usr/lib/python3.6/ssl.py"", line 1047, in shutdown
    socket.shutdown(self, how)

```
have looked at the code, and this message is generated here on the line assigning ts
variable in sr_message.py:set_msg_time:

```
        parts       = self.time.split('.')
        ts          = time.strptime(parts[0]+"" +0000"", ""%Y%m%d%H%M%S %z"" )
        ep_msg      = calendar.timegm(ts)
 
```       
Processing continues fine, seems to have no ill effect, but very strange.
",{},{}
18496,IssuesEvent,2018-07-23 15:07:59+00:00,11309795,nmslib/nmslib,495813,rshest,37882366,nmslib,opened,"""Check failed"" in `createIndex` for sparse data containing zero rows",[],[],0,"When creating an index for sparse data from the Python wrapper (calling `createIndex` with `scipy.sparse.csr_matrix`), it fails if there are zero vectors in the input data.

Here's a minimal repro-case:
```python
import numpy as np
from scipy.sparse import csr_matrix 
import nmslib 

data = csr_matrix((3, 3), dtype=np.float64)
data[0, 0] = 1
data[1, 0] = 2

# uncomment the following line to get rid of an empty row (and a crash)
#data[2, 0] = 3 

index = nmslib.init(method='hnsw', space='cosinesimil_sparse', data_type=nmslib.DataType.SPARSE_VECTOR) 
index.addDataPointBatch(data)

index.createIndex({'M': 30, 'indexThreadQty': 4, 'efConstruction': 100, 'post' : 0}) 
```

This results in:
```
Check failed: obj1->datalength() > 0
...
RuntimeError: Check failed: it's either a bug or inconsistent data!
```

Uncommenting the line `data[2, 0] = 3` in the above snippet makes it work.

Possibly some internal data structures do not get initialized when loading the data from Python (in case there are empty rows in `csr_matrix`)?",{},{}
18506,IssuesEvent,2018-07-02 11:52:04+00:00,80946973,lark-parser/lark,2574064,bemichel,38646335,lark-parser,closed,Lark does not understand space ?,[],[],1,"[testLarkSpace-py.txt](https://github.com/lark-parser/lark/files/2154978/testLarkSpace-py.txt)
Always try to understand haw to parse Fortran File with Lark !
You can see that I translate some stuff from F2x project (see attach file) 
and try first to parse declaration fortran lines like : 
```fortran
       INTEGER(kind=4), DIMENSION(ific1-1:ific2+1) :: a
``` 
and when I try to run the attach file : 
```python
from lark import Lark, Tree, InlineTransformer, UnexpectedInput
from lark.tree import pydot__tree_to_png

parser = Lark('''
start : program+

// ----------------------------------
// |            TERMS               |
// ----------------------------------
// Literal constants
// =================
T_CHAR_CONSTANT   : /((\'[^\']*\')+)|((""[^""]*"")+)/
T_DIGIT_STRING    : /[0-9]+/
BINARY_CONSTANT   : /([bB]\'[01]+\')|([bB]""[01]+"")/
OCTAL_CONSTANT    : /([oO]\'[0-7]+\')|([oO]""[0-7]+"")/
HEX_CONSTANT      : /([zZ]\'[0-9a-fA-F]+\')|([zZ]""[0-9a-fA-F]+"")/
T_PERIOD_EXPONENT : /(\.[0-9]+[EedD][+-]?[0-9]+)|(\.[EedD][+-]?[0-9]+)|(\.[0-9]+)|([0-9]+[eEdD][+-]?[0-9]+)/

// Operators
// =========
T_DEFINED_OP     : /\.[a-zA-Z]+\./

T_ASTERISK       : /\*/
T_COLON          : /:/

...


type_declaration_stmt : (label)? declaration_type_spec ((T_COMMA attr_spec)* T_COLON_COLON)? entity_decl_list // end_of_stmt

end_of_stmt  : (T_SEMICOLON (T_EOL)?)+  | (T_EOL)+   | T_EOF

%ignore LINE_COMMENT
%ignore PREPROCESS_LINE

program: type_declaration_stmt
''')

code = [""INTEGER(kind=4),DIMENSION(ific1-1:ific2+1)::a"",
        """"""INTEGER(kind=4),DIMENSION(ific1-1:ific2+1)::a
        """""",
        ""INTEGER(kind=4), DIMENSION(ific1-1:ific2+1) :: a"",
        """"""
        INTEGER(kind=4), DIMENSION(ific1-1:ific2+1) :: a
        INTEGER(kind=4), DIMENSION(ific1-1:ific2+1) :: b
        """"""
        ]
for c in code:
    try:
      tree = parser.parse(c)
      print tree.pretty()
    except UnexpectedInput as e:
      print ""Unable to parse : {}"".format(c)
      # print e
